snippet.textDisplay: Try it on a fairly untextured watercolor paper for doing your lines, then color it in with a marker that doesn't bleed its ink so easily. Your drying stages should still be long, but hopefully rewarding. That pen tends to work best in shorter strokes over longer ones.

snippet.textDisplay:
I do calligraphy and everyday writing with vintage fountain pens, and the occasional dip-pen.

Glass dip-pens have been around since the Victorian era. They hold a lot more ink per dip than a metal dip-nib or a quill pen. In the 1930s, there were even glass-nibbed fountain pens.

When you write with a dip-nib or fountain pen, you need to use a very light hand. The ink flows by capillary action, which requires no pressure at all. Unlike a biro (ballpoint) that needs a very heavy hand to make it write.

When you write or draw with liquid ink, it takes a while to dry. The thicker you lay it on, the longer it takes to dry. The bonus is that there are thousands of inks to try, from all around the world. Even vintage inks that are 80 years old.
snippet.textOriginal:

Glass dip-pens have been around since the Victorian era.   They hold a lot more ink per dip than a metal dip-nib or a quill pen.  In the 1930s, there were even glass-nibbed fountain pens.

When you write with a dip-nib or fountain pen, you need to use a very light hand.  The ink flows by capillary action, which requires no pressure at all.  Unlike a biro (ballpoint) that needs a very heavy hand to make it write.

When you write or draw with liquid ink, it takes a while to dry.  The thicker you lay it on, the longer it takes to dry.  The bonus is that there are thousands of inks to try, from all around the world.  Even vintage inks that are 80 years old.

snippet.textDisplay: First comment on one of your vids which is weird because I picked up drawing because of you. Anyways I love my dip pens (no glass here) for when I want some rigid yet flexible lines be it a script or  where you want a predictable transition between thick and thin. My bristle brush pen for more loose feeling lines (still getting the hang of it) and for all other inking just some fine liners. The glass dip pens look really good for writing if you were gunna do some copperplate or spencerian script but otherwise I think fall flat. That time between dips is impressive though.
